description:
src/lib.rs has multiple 'map_err(|e| SecretError::Backend { ... source: e.into() })' closures. The pattern that idiomatic Rust prefers is a From conversion plus the '?' operator:

  impl From<azure_core::Error> for SecretError { ... }

would let call sites use '?' directly. The complication is that *which* SecretError variant to produce depends on the kind (NotFound / Unavailable / Backend). That cannot be expressed by From alone.

The right idiomatic shape is a private helper:

  fn classify_kv_error(e: azure_core::Error) -> SecretError {
      if is_not_found(&e) { SecretError::NotFound }
      else if is_transient(&e) { SecretError::Unavailable { backend: BACKEND, source: e.into() } }
      else { SecretError::Backend { backend: BACKEND, source: e.into() } }
  }

then call sites are: '.map_err(classify_kv_error)?'. Removes the duplicated branching at lines 256-269 and 343-356, makes the policy a single function, and is the right place to add unit tests (see crate-secretsx-bdu0.8).

This is an error-handling idiom point: the 'duplicate the if/else ladder at every call site' shape is non-idiomatic for a stable classification policy.
